[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating dynamic access in tests**\n\nI'm considering why the tracing agent excludes dynamic access from tests or user code. It seems to only track dynamic access in target classes, but direct invocations should still apply. I wonder if the InvokerHelper is caching methods and using generated MetaMethod, but it still calls the class$ method, which leads me to think about Class.forName. However, maybe the method name \"class$\" is seen as invalid within the Groovy MOP. There's quite a bit to unpack!\n\n**Considering Java package visibility**\n\nI'm thinking about whether `java.beans.Statement` can invoke package-private methods. But it seems like I can't place a Java test in the same package as `io.restassured.internal.http` since the guidelines say to keep tests outside library packages. That means I can't directly call package-private methods. It's interesting to ponder how Java's access control shapes development practices. I wonder if there are any workarounds or best practices to navigate this while still maintaining clean code.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0f3e2f713d8de9d4016a283f2583bc8190823e7273720658a3\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKD9LM1YjMg_6KgQTMcC5NPcOi3oc5gwyFd_qN0-NHtf9r8zDY23qcaU1q0XPw1G4C1ZPLNBrvhb4EZOkItDUcG1sfS3qLHU0P98iep3AbgxKh-alsLGLTK8wLC5S-y5IlltB0IDylGy-OCH7pF_xK1oxxlCdZ_QKGKCKgM5VdxpTIF3XFRN36djuiRNJxj7e4mimgB5bs-JlCQ4ZA2yFf4C7XLnvEJYRhelkt_pQa8Dvk_mn185I6fNGMtt1twv9HdyVlIvsRNHv3dkNQn-I8a_yoJbtxW8iBsmRuAbuOoqCnI5EmW-DnFTHUjneT99Xy5YcEiT6FQQO6wkwY9JXH8t_uBjae4l2NwoZtPqwGVCe4I3VUDucDl663gwWOL77HysckVHayMzjrrh2G4GDvCuioHA5OzCTJkD1ifz09kSYX6atLjg63fF0ZrUaBUT4eN9YdGwlAoXP_2edqbdiqaIGkLqnja9cLxuB7NLGpZAocG8aa-IcSv7ubwQHWvQeP8AkeAybdmS2gfMJgQwtF6DUuFixgeOslctO2Iz7H6oXYgkB1tjiXzpn9unSdXOYbREp33796GmsUxtJKMB0XeLdbeITqx1d7tmWb32vfILPrywqfrnX382pW2S06b2JfVNK9cGsuTe8RX14Lu96YZcaoQBZ-npgEc39b