hods and using generated MetaMethod, but it still calls the class$ method, which leads me to think about Class.forName. However, maybe the method name \\\"class$\\\" is seen as invalid within the Groovy MOP. There's quite a bit to unpack!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java package visibility**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether `java.beans.Statement` can invoke package-private methods. But it seems like I can't place a Java test in the same package as `io.restassured.internal.http` since the guidelines say to keep tests outside library packages. That means I can't directly call package-private methods. It's interesting to ponder how Java's access control shapes development practices. I wonder if there are any workarounds or best practices to navigate this while still maintaining clean code.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ntcktSl3tTWpANEy6EQXRlWs|fc_0f3e2f713d8de9d4016a283f4bea44819080e5cfca44d61300", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"class\\$\\(\" -g'*.groovy' /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/main/extracted/io/restassured/internal/http && for c in ContentTypeExtractor CharsetExtractor BoundaryExtractor; do echo $c; javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/1bc7b4c046c2e00a37bf78f2d9d7b41a43fdd5d1/rest-assured-5.5.0.jar -c -p io.restassured.internal.http.$c | grep -n \"class\\$\\|Class.forName\\|ldc.*class\" | head -20; done", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2849, "output": 1254, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 37895, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781022498765, "responseId": "resp_0f3e2f713d8de9d4016a283f236838819091779aa5d84fafae"}}
